******
[1] Delaware
Date: Fri 24 Aug 2012
Source: The Republic, WDEL-AM/Associated Press (AP) report [edited]
http://www.therepublic.com/view/story/f4817ccfa1984dda959c5bb8605bf1d2


Delaware wildlife officials are not concerned about an insect-borne disease that's killing deer.

However, the Department of Natural Resources and Environmental Control [DNREC] does want residents to report dead deer, for research purposes.

DNREC officials tell WDEL [Newstalk Radio] (http://bit.ly/Qaimvf) that epizootic hemorrhagic disease, or EHD, likely won't have any long-term ramifications for Delaware's deer population. The disease has been killing deer throughout North America. It does not affect humans or livestock. This year [2012], 31 deer have died from EHD in Delaware so far. The last significant EHD outbreak was in 2007, when more than 132 deer were killed.

