[2] Ohio
Date: Sat 25 Aug 2012
Source: The News-Herald [edited]
http://news-herald.com/articles/2012/08/25/sports/nh5885725.txt


Ohio is beginning to see the arrival of the drought-driven epizootic hemorrhagic disease (EHD), with 13 captive-raised deer in Middlefield Township recently dying from the almost-always fatal disease.

Mike Tonkovich, the Ohio Division of Wildlife's deer management administrator, said the Ohio Department of Agriculture has confirmed the 13 deaths from a herd of about 120 captive-raised animals.

It is the state's Agriculture Department that now administers captive deer-breeding operations.

According to Tonkovich, a northern Portage County landowner has reported seeing several dead deer along the Upper Cuyahoga River, just downstream from Geauga County. Other dead deer have been found along a water course in Monroe County.

"That would be a good indicator of the presence of EHD, though not for certain," Tonkovich said. "We need a freshly dead deer to confirm this."

EHD is a typically fatal viral disease. It is found in wild ruminants like deer, causing extensive internal bleeding and is transmitted solely by a midge, a flying critter about the size of a ground black pepper flake.

A characteristic of the disease is its sudden onset. An infected deer loses its appetite and fear of humans, grows progressively weaker, salivates excessively, and finally becomes unconscious.

Due to an accompanying high fever, an infected deer is often found sick or dead along or in bodies of water. It is here where the disease is carried by midges, super-tiny insects that need a blood host.

Importantly, biologists say, there is no evidence humans can contract the EHD virus.

The previous serious EHD outbreaks that happened in Ohio were in 2005 and 2007.

[Byline: Jeffrey L Frischkorn]

